==Old English==
===Etymology===
Common Germanic *''[[naht-]]'', whence also Old High German ''[[naht]]'', Old Norse ''[[nátt]]''
Cognates include [[w:Ancient Greek language|Greek (Ancient)]]      <!-- Please note that this makes sense, so Greek (Modern) and Greek (Ancient) are listed both under 'G' --> ''[[νύξ]]'' (nyx), Latin ''[[nox]]'', [[w:Gothic language|Gothic]] ''[[𐌽𐌰𐌷𐍄𐍃]]'' (nahts), German ''[[Nacht]]'' and Russian ''[[ночь]]'' (noch').
===Noun===
'''niht''' ''f''

